Yojimbo is a great film because it shows the hereditary "professional deformation" of the warrior aristocracy. Even when the samurai is all dilapidated and rotten trying to make his own fortune he cannot help but serve others. Like the beaver pet building a dam out of plush toys.

It's like watching a sheep dog trying to live like a wild dog or a wolf in the wilderness but his instincts still take over when he sees a flock of sheep and he starts herding them together and guarding them. He's conditioned to do it by his nature. "D√©formation professionnelle".

That scene where he sees the man whose wife was taken by the gamblers watching her get raped through a hole in the wall and is absolutely disgusted with him yet cannot stop himself from going to save her and reunite them. He's simply "eugenically" bred to selflessly serve others.

When I was in school I was always puzzled at those students who when a teacher asked them some question they couldn't answer would just freeze and fall silent staring like a deer in front of a truck's lights instead of immediately starting to bullshit away like I always would do.

Like some people just don't have the instinct to bargain and talk, they sit there frozen while the professor or whoever keeps repeatedly asking them stuff and begging them to say anything. Total terror. Meanwhile even if you know nothing you'll still be OK if you can bullshit it.

There was one Survivorman episode where Les Stroud actually had a cold on the first day, sore throat, running a fever, etc. and he just filmed through the sickness building a shelter and searching for food all while pretty ill. This is real life. Gotta get good... Very admirable.

Others would have just delayed a few days until they were ok and started filming afterwards but he always wants it to be as real as possible. Some days you wake up sick as a dog and still have to do something important, life or death...
